 "cells": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e8cad372",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Simulating photonic lantern observables"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8b6eb487",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This tutorial is on how to simulate photonic lantern outputs for given astronomical scene.\n",
    "\n",
    "The lantern observable simulation consists of two parts: 1) focal-plane field decomposition into spatial modes and 2) projecting them on the lantern's measurement basis, defined by transfer matrix.\n",
    "\n",
    "Mathematical framework is detailed in [Kim et al. 2024c](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2024JATIS..10d5004K).\n",
    "\n",
    "The first step is done using ``sim.PLOverlapCalculator``. The second step is done by ``sim.Device`` as a transfer matrix as an input."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "ceafa498",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from PLsim import simulator as sim\n",
    "from PLsim import lantern as l\n",
    "from PLsim import scene as s"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0efb7cd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The ``PLOverlapCalculator`` class calculates the spatial modes of the multimode input of the lantern and decomposes focal-plane light in this mode basis. One needs to input the properties of the beam (unobstructed circular aperture is assumed) and the lantern's multimode geometry and refractive indices (LP modes are assumed, with the geometry of circular step-index fiber). "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1c71a94d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For the default refractive index settings, about 6 um core radius gives 3-moded lantern, 10 um gives 6-moded lantern, and 16.5 um gives 19-moded lantern."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "52c9f88c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Available modes:  [(0, 1, 'cos'), (1, 1, 'cos'), (1, 1, 'sin')]\n",
      "Calculated k0, V, modes\n",
      "LP modes stored in self.u0s\n",
      "Coupling efficiency: 0.8167813749438008\n",
      "Pupil functions calculated and stored in self.u0s_pupil\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# let's simulate 3-port lantern with focal ratio of 5.3\n",
    "oc = sim.PLOverlapCalculator(dim = 385, # defines the resolution of the grid. use odd numbers.\n",
    "                             telescope_diameter = 10, # in meters\n",
    "                             wavelength = 1.55e-6, # in meters\n",
    "                             nclad = 1.444, # lantern core refractive index\n",
    "                             njack = 1.444 - 5.5e-3, # lantern cladding refractive index\n",
    "                             rclad = 6e-6, # lantern core radius in meters,\n",
    "                             focal_length = 53, # focal length in meters. if not provided,\n",
    "                             # it searches for the focal length that gives the best coupling efficiency.\n",
    "                             )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "04243f22",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now define the lantern's transfer matrix and the ``Device`` class. Let's assume a mode-selective lantern, which has an identity matrix."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "f0f7377c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "U = np.identity(3)\n",
    "device_PL = sim.Device(lantern_matrix = U, verbose=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4263f68b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Simulate PL response to any astronomical scene"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ba7057fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 1: simulate point source response"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7c14ed2a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Simulation of point source response is done by computing overlaps using ``oc.compute_overlap``."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "02cdcee6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# positions in radians\n",
    "xpos = 0 \n",
    "ypos = 5e-3 / 206265 # let's consider slight misalignment in one axis by 5 mas\n",
    "\n",
    "overlap = oc.compute_overlap(xpos, ypos)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "1831cef5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 300x150 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "intens = device_PL.calculate_output_intensities(overlap)[0][0]\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(3,1.5))\n",
    "plt.bar(range(len(intens)), intens)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('ports')\n",
    "plt.xticks(range(len(intens)), ['port 1', 'port 2', 'port 3'])\n",
    "plt.ylabel('intensity (a.u.)')\n",
    "plt.title('Mode-selective lantern')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e96359a4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 2: simulate coupling maps"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4c87a376",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Use ``oc.compute_overlap_grid_2d`` to compute overlaps in a 2D grid"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "80fbc919",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fov = 100e-3 / 206265 # field of view in radians\n",
    "ngrid = 15 # number of grid points along one axis\n",
    "\n",
    "overlap_grid = oc.compute_overlap_grid_2d(fov, ngrid, xoffset=0, yoffset=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "58a8453f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "intens_grid = device_PL.calculate_output_intensities(overlap_grid)[0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "5746c7ba",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

   ],

    "fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(6,2))\n",

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a9fe0ab5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 3: simulate an extended star"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2027e07d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Use ``oc.compute_overlap_disk`` to compute overlaps for extended star"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "c60b0e2a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# simulate an extended star, with radius of 10 mas and ellipticity of 1 (circular)\n",
    "overlap_star = oc.compute_overlap_disk(radius = 10e-3/206265, ellip=1)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "dbe85655",
   "metadata": {},

   ],
   "source": [
    "intens_star = device_PL.calculate_output_intensities(overlap_star)[0][0]\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(3,1.5))\n",
    "plt.bar(range(len(intens_star)), intens_star)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('ports')\n",
    "plt.xticks(range(len(intens_star)), ['port 1', 'port 2', 'port 3'])\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "97ec06e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 4: simulate complex scenes\n",
    "\n",
    "With these point source and extended source overlap calculators, most astronomical scenes can be simulated (as long as they are incoherent)! Any source intensity distribution can be represented as sum of point sources' intensities -- so the grid of overlaps (`compute_overlap_grid_2d`) can be used to generate reponse to complex scenes. For simulating finite stellar sizes, `compute_overlap_disk` is useful as the grid approach would require too fine samplings.\n",
    "\n",
    "Once a grid of overlaps are calculated, for example 25x25 resolution, you can simulate any image of 25x25 resolution using that overlap grid -- no need to recompute!\n",
    "\n",
    "Also tip-tilt jitter during an exposure can be simulated this way. A very long exposures, effects of random jitter would be similar to finite size star."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4658aa47",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Change the lantern properties - use a different transfer matrix"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fffcf3f8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The nice thing about this structure is that once overlap is computed, one can use whatever transfer matrix to simulate the observables for different lantern transfer matrix.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's consider a random unitary matrix, representing a standard lantern."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "d03efb09",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.stats import unitary_group\n",
    "np.random.seed(123456)\n",
    "U_random = unitary_group.rvs(3)\n",
    "device_PL_standard = sim.Device(lantern_matrix = U_random, verbose=False)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d39786e3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Simulate lantern outputs through atmosphere\n",
    "\n",
    "A quick example of the effects of atmospheric turbulence on lantern observables.\n",
    "\n",
    "The phase aberration would change the overlaps. Calculating overlaps with aberration is done by `oc.aberrate(phase_screen)` where phase_screen is the pupil plane phase aberration map.\n",
    "\n",
    "I will use hcipy to simulate phase screens and use parameters that look similar to ExAO correction."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "ed117d52",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.image.NonUniformImage at 0x7fc091c46110>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 15,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import hcipy as hc\n",
    "seeing = 0.05 # arcsec \n",
    "outer_scale = 40 # meter\n",
    "tau0 = 0.005 # seconds\n",
    "\n",
    "fried_parameter = hc.seeing_to_fried_parameter(seeing)\n",
    "Cn_squared = hc.Cn_squared_from_fried_parameter(fried_parameter, 500e-9) # at 500 nm\n",
    "velocity = 0.314 * fried_parameter / tau0\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(0)\n",
    "layer = hc.InfiniteAtmosphericLayer(oc.prop.pupil_grid, Cn_squared, outer_scale, velocity)\n",
    "\n",
    "phase_screen_phase = layer.phase_for(oc.prop.wavelength) # in radian\n",
    "phase_screen_opd = phase_screen_phase * (oc.prop.wavelength / (2 * np.pi)) * 1e6\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "hc.imshow_field(phase_screen_opd, vmin=-np.pi, vmax=np.pi, cmap='RdBu')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 88,
   "id": "21a22dff",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n",
      "Cross-correlated pupil plane LP modes stored in self.full_ccpupils\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "dt = 0.05 # cadence\n",
    "n = 10\n",
    "overlaps = []\n",
    "focal_fields =[]\n",
    "for t in np.linspace(0, n*dt, n):\n",
    "    layer.t = t\n",
    "\n",
    "    phase_screen_phase = layer.phase_for(oc.prop.wavelength) \n",
    "    focal_field=oc.prop.propagator(hc.Wavefront(hc.Field(oc.prop.wf.electric_field * np.exp(1j * phase_screen_phase), grid=oc.prop.pupil_grid), wavelength=oc.prop.wavelength))\n",
    "    focal_fields.append(focal_field)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # calculate overlaps with aberration\n",
    "    oc.aberrate(phase_screen_phase)\n",
    "    overlaps.append(oc.compute_overlap(0,0)) # point source at the center\n",
    "\n",
    "# reset aberration\n",
    "oc.unaberrate()\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 89,
   "id": "4d2d064e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# now calculate intensities with the aberration\n",
    "intens_aberrated = device_PL.calculate_output_intensities(np.array(overlaps))[0]"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "from matplotlib.animation import FuncAnimation\n",
    "from IPython.display import HTML\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,3))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(121)\n",
    "ax2 = fig.add_subplot(122)\n",
    "\n",
    "def animate(i):\n",
    "    ax.clear()\n",
    "    hc.imshow_field(focal_fields[i].intensity, ax=ax)\n",
    "    ax2.clear()\n",
    "    ax2.bar(range(3), intens_aberrated[i])\n",
    "    ax2.set_ylim([0, 3.5e-5])\n",
    "    ax2.set_xticks(range(3), ['port 1', 'port 2', 'port 3'])\n",
    "\n",
    "anim = FuncAnimation(fig, animate, n)\n",
    "HTML(anim.to_html5_video())\n"
   ]
